<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species has a very similar appearance and size to several 
<taxonomicName authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species which also have three or four denticles on declivital interstriae 2. The two genera are easily separated by the pronotal disc sculpturing: punctate in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and asperate in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiodmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiodmus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiodmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
